Indeed, unlversltles\nare considered as partners with government and industryinthe nation\'s aerospace program. NASA\'s\nobjective is to have them bring their scientific, engineering, and social research competence to bear\non aerospace problems and on the broader social, economic, and international implications of\nNASA\'s technical and scientific programs. It is expected that, in so dorng, universities will strengthen\nboth their research and their educational capabilities to contribute more effectively to the nat~onal\nwell-being.\n\n\'\n\n.\n\n.\n:\n.\n\n,\n\nNASA Field Centers and certain Headquarters Program Offices provide funds for those R&D\nactivities in universities which contribute to the mission needs of that particular NASA element.\nAlthough NASA h a s n o predetermined amount of money t o devote to university activities, the\neffort funded each year is substantial. (See the bar chart on the next page.) This annual report is\none means of documenting the NASA-university relationship, frequently denoted. collectively. as\nNASA\'s University Program.\nThe Office of University Affairs (OUA) serves as a focal point\'for NASA\'s relationships with\ncolleges and universities. One of its roles is to provide information on the NASA University\nProgram. The present document is designed to serve several purposes arid a wide range of audiences\nfrom private individuals to NASA employees. The emphasis is on the technical content of the\nprogram, ratherthan on fiscal data, which is available separately from OUA. As some terminology\nwill not be familiar lo all readers, a "User\'s Guide" is included to facilitate the fullest use of the\nmaterial related to the interests of any particular reader.\nInformation on obtaining reports resulting from these projects may be obtained from:\nScientific and Technical Information Office. Code KS. Washington. DC 20546.\n\n-\n\nFrnnk D. Hansing. Director\nOfli~u: University Affairs\nof\n\niii\n\nNASA.\n\nNASA OBLIGATIONS TO UNIVERSITIES\n\nFISCAL YEARS\nNotes: 1 . CASE Fields of Science and Engineering\nThe National Science ~ o u n d a i i o n(NSF) on behalf o f the committee on Academic Science and\nEngineering(CASE) of the Federal Council f o r Science and Technology ( F C S T ) operates a\ngovernment-wide system for collecting and analyzing data on support to colleges and universities.\nCo1lege.s\nParticipating agencies report annually to NSF which i n turn, issues Support to Uttivrrsitie.~.\nI\nc\nd I\n1 1 . ~ 1 i t t i o t 1 . CASE Fields, used in the extensive tabulations contained in\nThe\nthat document, form the only consistent classification system for government sponsored research.\nThe lields are listed i n full in Appendix 9.\n\nIV. Cross-Indexes\nThe cross-indexed Appendices are related to the citations (descriptions) by the accession number\n(item 3). The accession number has meaning only in this report; i t i s i n no way permanently associated\nwith.nor does it uniquely identify a specific grant or contract anywhere except i n the present report.\nAccession numbers are assigned sequentially to the citations, beginning with 1000. Thus, when an\nentry of interest is identified\'in\' any one o f the Appendices, the associated accession number allows\nready location o f the l u l l description i n the body o f the report.\nAppendix A\n\n-\n\nGiven pnly the grant or contract number this index enables the reader\nt o locate\'the citation. The first page tells how to distinguish grants\nfrom contracts.\n\nAppendix B - This index provides rapid access to all projects i n a particular area of\nendeavor, as defined by the CASE Fields. This listing i s also easily\nused to determine the institutions and principal investigators conducting\nN A S A projects i n a field.\n..\n\n.\n\nAppendix C\n\n-\n\n.\n\nT h e types o f effort sponsored by each N A S A installation may be\ndetermined from this index.\n\nAppendix D - This index,is included primarily for the convenience of internal N A S A\nreaders. However, the RTOP, per\'se, may be of considerable interest\nto external users. See V, below.\n\nV . Source Code and RTOP\nThe last line of the citation (item I I)contains 1-3 sets of numbers i n parenthesis. By interpreting the\ncoding a great deal of additional information o n a project may be obtained. The first set i s current\nand is the most useful; the second and third sets, i f present, generally represent historical data.\n\nEach set of numbers is further divided into two groups separated by a blank space. The first group\ncontains source coding, while the second is the "Research and Technology Operating Plan" (RTOP).\n\nSource Codins (Item I la)\n\nThe first two-digit number identifies the NASA installation (by the code given in 11,\nabove) which has most recently added funds to the project. Disagreement between this\ninstallation and the technical officer location usually indicates that \'responsibility for a\nproject is being transferred.\nThe second number identifies the major NASA Program Office responsible for the research,\nas follows: 200.299, Office of Technology Utilization: 300-399, Office of University Affairs;\n400-499. Office of Energy Programs; 500-599, Office of Tracking and Data Acquisition;\n600-699. Office of Applications; 700.799, Office of Aeronautics and Space Technology;\n800-899, Office of Space Science; and 900-999. Office of Manned Space Flight.\n\nRTOP (Item I Ib)\nThe RTOP. "Research and Technology Operating Plan" number indicates a broad technical\narea in which NASA desires to achieve certain objectives. Numerous projects, conducted\nboth in-house and out-of-house and with all classes of performers may contribute to the\nobjective of a single RTOP. Detailed descriptions of the RTOPs, including names of\nresponsible individuals and extensive cross-indexing are published annually. The FY74\nedition entitled Research and Tech~rology\nOperarirrg Pla~rSu~tmtar?may be purchased from\n(NTIS), Springfield, Virginia 22151, for $3.00.\nthe National Technical Information S c ~ i c e\n($2.50 additional for Foreign mailing.)\n\nNASA\'s UNIVERSITY PROGRAM\nNCR 01401424\nAlabama A&M Ulllversity\nRocket engine t h w t calculation and analysls\nmbdo!"\n\nP<M\n\nUl/Ol/73-06/M/74\n. .\nNCR 014014U\nNabam A&M UnlrPnity\nID\nDO\nMHZ shuttle. slation and satellite mmmunktions analysis\nm nl m\n4 .b\n\nP e M\n\n03/30/7l43/31/74\nPlln l ~ r a\n\nLamine. There may be a second technical officer, shown in the citation, at the same or a\ndifferent installation. Abbreviations used for locations are: ARC, Ames Research Center;\nFRC, Flight Research Center; GSFC, Goddard Space Flight Center; KSC, Kennedy Space\nCenter, JSC, Johnson Space Center; LARC, Langley Research Center; LERC, Lewis Research\nCenter; MSFC, Marshall Space Flight Center; WFC, Wallops Flight Center and HQ,\nHeadquarters. The HQ designator carries suffixed letters identifying individual Headquarters\noffices; and explanation of these identifiers and full addresses for all installations may be\nfound.in the prefatory pages. The key for the "Field Code" column is in Appendix B.\n\nTECH\nOFF\nLOC\n\nTECHNICAL\nOFFICER\n\nARC\nARC\nARC\nARC\nARC\nARC\nARC\'\nARC\nARC\nARC\nARC\nARC\nARC\nARC\nARC\n\'ARC\nARC\nARC\nARC\nARC\nARC\nARC\nARC\nARC\nARC\nARC\nARC\nARC\nARC\nARC\nARC\nARC\nARC\nARC\nARC\nARC\nARC\nARC\nARC\nARC\n\nHaines, R.
